<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>DDB0155</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Mayor of London – Written evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Mayor of London strongly welcomes the Government’s ongoing commitment to removing the unnecessary and destructive bureaucracy that is frustrating London’s businesses, blocking innovation and wasting money that could be better spent on driving forward jobs and growth.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Efforts to scrap and reform regulation are to be welcomed, and the Mayor would support a more systematic and comprehensive audit of burdens on public bodies, particularly the GLA group. The GLA would be very keen to contribute to such an audit in the near future.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The draft Deregulation Bill contains a raft of measures to remove legislative barriers and burdens which are out of date or unnecessary. The Mayor is suggesting some minor but important additions to the draft Bill which will:</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.5pt; padding-left:9.05pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">help ensure that London’s energy infrastructure is consummate with the city’s future growth;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.5pt; padding-left:9.05pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">tidy up the wasteful existing legislation on transport byelaws in London;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.5pt; padding-left:9.05pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">prevent unnecessary and expensive duplication of accounts across local government; and</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.5pt; padding-left:9.05pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">update</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> out-of-date legislation to include ticketless payments in London.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Energy Infrastructure</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">The Problem</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The current regulations governing the provision of new electricity infrastructure in London </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">are out-of-step with the needs of the capital and possibly other UK cities,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> delaying important new developments and discouraging investment. It is concerning that the ease of getting electricity connections in the UK</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> ranks a poor 62</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">nd</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> out of 185 economies (and very poorly among other EU states) in the World Bank’s recent ‘Ease of Doing Business’ survey. This clearly needs to improve. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">evere restrictions currently prevent electricity Distribution Network Operators (DNOs) from installing more capacity strategically in the network and making electricity available to new developments without first receiving a formal request for a connection to the system from a developer. This prohibits the required forward-looking strategic investment in the capital’s infrastructure.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This can lead to developers having to incur unexpected and significant costs themselves to set up electricity infrastructure, as it will not otherwise be available in sufficient time, or else withdraw from a potential site entirely. Developers are understandably already voicing their concerns, and failure to take action threatens London’s competitiveness as a leading world city.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The current restrictions, which are the result of a combination of the provisions of the Electricity Act 1989, its regulations and the way Ofgem interprets and exercises its regulatory functions, curtail successful forward-planning. This acts as a powerful disincentive to developers looking for new areas to invest.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">The Solution</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Government’s proposal to require the regulators, including Ofgem, to have a regard to promoting economic growth will be an important and welcome reform.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Mayor believes that DNOs in London must be given substantially more scope and flexibility, in consultation with key stakeholders including the Mayor, to reduce the level of network stress by facilitating strategic investment in London’s electricity infrastructure. This must be done through regulatory reform.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Transport byelaws</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">The Problems</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Transport for London (TfL) has the power to make byelaws relating to some, but not all, of its different services (eg: railways, road transport premises and tramlink). However, these powers are all covered by different, variant legislation including the </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Greater London Authority Act 1999 (railway) and the London Transport Act 1969 (road transport premises).</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Each of these pieces of legislation contains different rules, processes and requirements, leading to complexity and unnecessary cost when byelaws are drafted, planned and implemented. The differing rules also lead to anomalies such as an offence having different penalties depending on which TfL service it is committed on. The maximum penalty for offences is £1000 on rail services, £500 on piers and £20 on the Woolwich Ferry.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Significant wasteful costs can occur when TfL introduces a policy across all its services. For example, when the alcohol ban was brought in across the TfL network in 2008 it required several different processes and different consultations for the users of each of the effected services. This delayed time in advising of changes created additional expense to the exercise.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">It is frustrating that TfL does not have the power to make byelaws relating to a very critical part of its transport network and largest carrier of passengers - London’s bus services. Currently, conduct on all national buses is dictated by the Public Service Vehicle regulations, preventing TfL from implementing London-wide and consistent policies across its transport network, such as the 2008 alcohol ban. As well as adding another layer of complexity, this mismatched approach prevents TfL from rolling out consistent passenger information across the network which is unduly expensive for TfL and confusing for passengers. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">There is also confusion around the alcohol ban with respect to Designated Public Place Orders (DPPOs) which councils put in place in areas where nuisance and disturbance is </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">evidenced as a result of alcohol consumption. Where DPPOs are in place this has the anomalous effect of automatically nullifying TfL’s alcohol ban byelaws under the provisions of Section 13 of the Criminal Justice and Police Act 2001.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">The Solutions</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Mayor is calling for a uniform byelaw-making power for TfL with one set of consultation and notification requirements and a single confirmation procedure. Consolidating the powers that already exist will save time and money, reducing unnecessary bureaucracy, cost, and confusion for travellers.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Mayor also suggests that the power to make byelaws relating to London’s buses is devolved to TfL to ensure a joined-up approach across the transport network. Crucially, this small change would ensure that multiple different regulations no longer need to be enforced on different services and that TfL can instead focus on the specific public transport issues that London faces.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The confusion around the alcohol ban and Designated Public Place Orders could be very simply solved by amending Section 15 of the Criminal Justice and Police Act 2001 to exclude TfL’s byelaws from the list of byelaws to which the Section applies. This would help to ensure consistency across the network and amend a pointless and obstructive piece of bureaucracy.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Accounting and audit requirements</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">The Problem</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Currently the Greater London Authority (GLA) and TfL are required to prepare duplicate accounts for themselves and their group holding subsidiary companies, wasting time and public money. This costly anomaly applies across the whole of local government wherever a UK council has a holding subsidiary with a group of daughter subsidiary companies.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">TfL has a subsidiary holding company, TTL, under which sit TfL’s 25 “daughter” subsidiary companies. TfL must prepare two sets of group accounts: one set for TfL itself (which includes TTL and the daughter subsidiaries) under CIPFA rules and another set for TTL (which includes the same 25 daughter subsidiaries) under Companies Act accounting rules. Both sets of group accounts must also be separately audited under their respective regimes.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Efforts have already been made to minimise unnecessary duplication elsewhere through the Companies Act 2006, but these exemptions are not available to local authorities. This is because the exemptions are only available where group company accounts are prepared in accordance with international accounting standards or the EC’s Seventh Directive.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The relevant CIPFA rules do not, however, fully comply with either.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">It currently costs TfL around £100k per year (direct and indirect costs) in duplicated activities, such as separate local authority and companies accounts and audit teams </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">within TfL’s external auditor, to work to produce the accounts and undertake their audit. This is an unnecessary waste of money.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">The Solution</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Mayor is calling on the Government to make a simple amendment to the Companies Act 2006 to exempt local authorities from the requirement to prepare duplicate group accounts for themselves and for their holding subsidiaries, given that their accounts already conform to CIPFA’s rigorous standards. This is an easy change that would save time and money.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Ticketless Payments</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">The Problem</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Schedule 17 of the GLA Act 1999 relating to penalty fares is out of date in that it does not acknowledge that modern ticketing may involve smart cards, contactless cards, and other methods of payment. Consequently it is not clear on the face of the legislation that modern methods of payment are accepted for travel, and the requirements specified in Schedule 17 are only valid for paper tickets which does not reflect current practice. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Mayor is also unable to use discretion to create separate, lower penalty charges for certain groups of people, for example minors, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">which</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> would be fairer and help ensure that the penalty reflects the ability to pay.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">The Solution</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Simple amendments to the penalty fare provisions in Schedule 17 of the GLA Act would bring the Act fully up-to-date and modernise and allow the Mayor to set lower penalty charges where appropriate.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Mayor hopes that these minor but important amendments to the draft Deregulation Bill will be considered positively and looks forward to working with the Government as the Bill progresses through its Parliamentary stages. </span><a name="_GoBack"></a></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>